      "name": "Random Pots",
      "artisticStyle": "Product Illustration",
      "medium": "Digital Illustration",
      "creationDate": "2021",
      "insight": "ON FLOWERPOTS — An Exhibition\nInspired by Schopenhauer's belief that plants and animals, unlike humans, live entirely in the present — unburdened by regret or anticipation — this exhibition places the humble flowerpot at its center. Where human desire distorts reality and generates suffering, a plant simply receives what it is given and grows. The artist, who once confessed to wishing she could become a tree in a quiet forest, invites viewers to rediscover that same stillness through the living objects we so often overlook on our windowsills and desks.\n\nThe 100 works on display were created using a custom Generative Art system, in which individual elements — pot, plant, and background — are algorithmically combined to produce unexpected, unrepeatable compositions. Drawing on the card-collection rarity pioneered by early NFT projects, each piece is wholly unique. Hidden among the 100 is a single work featuring Aerides japonicum (나도 풍란), a critically endangered wild orchid disappearing from Korea's natural landscape — a quiet reminder that even the smallest artificial nature can carry the weight of what we stand to lose.",
      "url": "",
      "showThumbnailInGallery": true
    },
